SERIALIZATION\
- the process of writing a java object to some destination, as a bytestream\
- save the object and its state to disk or memory\
- why\
	pass java objects to remote hosts\
	serialize read queries from a database that will change rarely\
	post mortem analysis\
- primitives and arrays are serializable by default\
- the entire object tree will be serialized\
- multiple object references are saved only once\
- static variables are not serializable because they are not tied to any object instance\
- subclass of a superclass is automatically serializable\
- if you don\'92t want an instance variable to be serialized then mark it as \'91transient\'92\
\
NOTE: Every serializable class gets a version ID (serialVerisionUID) computed from class structure OR hand coded by programmer\
\
\
DESERIALIZATION\
- when deserializing, if there is a non-serializable ancestor of the object in question, then ancestor\'92s constructor will be run and any constructors above it (even if they are serializable)\
- instance variables that are non-transient situation will get their serialized state\
- instance variables that are transient will get default values\
\
the following changes will not affect the deserialization process (given serialVersionUID) has been specified\
- add/delete instance variables\
- make an instance variable as static\
- change instance variable from transient to non-transient\
- change access level of variables\
- add/remove classes to/from inheritance tree\
\
the following changes will affect deserialization\
- change instance variable\'92s type\
- make serializable class (anywhere in the object tree) non-serializable\
